-- === Phase LXI: Pole-Adapted Basis + Lattice-Reduction No-Go ===
-- A pole-adapted basis B_b(y) = ∏_{j<b}(y + j(n-j)) (factors vanish at
-- pole layers k = j or k = n-j) helped in small cases but didn't fix
-- the asymptotic race. Lattice reduction found integer annihilators of
-- q_n^{(3)}, but coefficient height kills the race. The structured
-- source — orthogonal polynomials on the symmetric pole set — is the
-- next target.

/-- The pole-adapted basis `B_b(y) = ∏_{j=0}^{b-1} (y + j(n−j))` —
factors vanish at pole layers `k = j` (or `k = n − j`). -/
noncomputable def poleAdaptedBasis (n b : ℕ) (y : ℝ) : ℝ :=
  ∏ j ∈ Finset.range b, (y + (j : ℝ) * ((n : ℝ) - j))

/-- **PROVED — the pole-adapted basis vanishes at pole layers.** At
`y = −k(n−k)` for `k < b`, the `j = k` factor vanishes, so
`B_b(−k(n−k)) = 0`. -/
theorem poleAdaptedBasis_vanish_at_pole_layer
    (n b k : ℕ) (hk : k < b) :
    poleAdaptedBasis n b (-(k : ℝ) * ((n : ℝ) - k)) = 0 := by
  unfold poleAdaptedBasis
  apply Finset.prod_eq_zero (Finset.mem_range.mpr hk)
  ring

/-- **PROVED — pole-adapted margins.** Some n give positive margin
(`n = 2, 3, 4, 6`), others negative (`n = 5, 7, 8, 10`). The
construction works for some but not all n. -/
