/-!
## Tier 73 — Prime–Herglotz de Branges Gate

The earlier tiers chase the *operator*. The operator is hard to see.
This tier chases the **response** instead — the logarithmic derivative
`R = Ξ'/Ξ` — which is *visible*: the zeros of `Ξ` are exactly the poles
of `R`. If the response is forced to be Herglotz/anti-Herglotz (a
Stieltjes transform of a positive spectral measure), the zeros are
forced onto the real mirror axis and the operator comes for free by
representation theory.

The attack line, made into Lean:

```
finite Hermitian determinant   (Tier 21 realDiagonal)
  → real-rooted polynomial      (rootProduct)
  → anti-Herglotz log-derivative   ← THIS TIER, proved unconditionally
  → limiting anti-Herglotz response  ← survives pointwise limits
  → de Branges / Hermite–Biehler gate
  → self-adjoint multiplication operator
  → real zeros of Ξ                  (Tier 16 Diamond)
  → RH
```

Unlike a list of necessary conditions, this tier proves a genuine
*positivity engine* unconditionally:

* **`rootSumResponse_antiHerglotz`** — the sum of simple poles over real
  roots `∑ 1/(z − rᵢ)` has non-positive imaginary part on the upper
  half-plane. (Each real pole contributes `−Im z / |z−rᵢ|² ≤ 0`.)
* **`rootProduct_logDeriv_eq_rootSum`** — the logarithmic derivative
  `P'/P` of a real-rooted polynomial *equals* that pole sum.
* **`realRooted_logDerivative_antiHerglotz`** — therefore the
  log-derivative of *any* real-rooted polynomial is anti-Herglotz.
  (On the upper half-plane every point is automatically a non-root,
  since the roots are real — so the identity holds with no side
  condition.)
* **`antiHerglotz_of_tendsto`** — anti-Herglotz is a *pointwise closed*
  condition, hence it survives locally uniform (indeed pointwise)
  limits.

These four feed the classification object `PrimeHerglotzLaw`: a
real-rooted polynomial approximation to `Ξ` together with a convergent
log-derivative response. Its response is then *provably* anti-Herglotz
(`PrimeHerglotzLaw.response_antiHerglotz`), and `Ξ` has only real zeros
(`PrimeHerglotzLaw.implies_RH`, via the Tier-16 Diamond). The no-go
`no_primeHerglotz_of_response_not_antiHerglotz` runs the sieve in
reverse: a response that fails anti-Herglotz can never arise from a
Hilbert–Pólya real-rooted approximation — a falsification lever.

Concrete de Branges objects (`UpperHalfPlane`, `SharpConjugate`,
`HermiteBiehlerDominance`, `HermiteBiehlerConcrete`) replace the
abstract `Prop`-fields of the Tier-36 `HermiteBiehlerFunction` with
real inequalities, and `HermiteBiehlerConcrete.toAbstract` records the
upgrade path.

No GoldenAlgebra-specific axiom appears in any Tier 73 proof.
-/

-- --- Tier 73.1 — Upper half-plane and Herglotz response laws --------

/-- **The open upper half-plane** as a predicate on `ℂ`. -/
def UpperHalfPlane (z : ℂ) : Prop := 0 < z.im

/-- **Herglotz response law.** `R` maps the open upper half-plane into
the closed upper half-plane: `0 ≤ Im R(z)` whenever `Im z > 0`. The
spectral-resolvent positivity condition. -/
def HerglotzResponseLaw (R : ℂ → ℂ) : Prop :=
  ∀ z : ℂ, 0 < z.im → 0 ≤ (R z).im

/-- **Anti-Herglotz response law.** `R` maps the open upper half-plane
into the closed *lower* half-plane: `Im R(z) ≤ 0` whenever `Im z > 0`.
This is the sign convention satisfied by the logarithmic derivative
`P'/P` of a real-rooted polynomial. -/
def AntiHerglotzResponseLaw (R : ℂ → ℂ) : Prop :=
  ∀ z : ℂ, 0 < z.im → (R z).im ≤ 0

/-- The anti-Herglotz law is the Herglotz law of the negated response:
the two sign conventions are interchangeable. -/
theorem antiHerglotz_iff_neg_herglotz (R : ℂ → ℂ) :
    AntiHerglotzResponseLaw R ↔ HerglotzResponseLaw (fun z => -(R z)) := by
  constructor
  · intro h z hz
    have hb := h z hz
    rw [Complex.neg_im]
    linarith
  · intro h z hz
    have hb := h z hz
    rw [Complex.neg_im] at hb
    linarith

-- --- Tier 73.2 — Real-root pole sum and the response polynomial -----

/-- **Linear-factor product** over real roots: `∏ᵢ (z − rᵢ)`. The
characteristic determinant of the real-diagonal matrix `realDiagonal r`
(see `rootProduct_eq_charDet`). -/
noncomputable def rootProduct {N : ℕ} (r : Fin N → ℝ) : ℂ → ℂ :=
  fun z => ∏ i : Fin N, (z - (r i : ℂ))

/-- **Real-root pole sum** `∑ᵢ 1/(z − rᵢ)`: the partial-fraction form of
the logarithmic derivative of `rootProduct r`. -/
noncomputable def rootSumResponse {N : ℕ} (r : Fin N → ℝ) : ℂ → ℂ :=
  fun z => ∑ i : Fin N, (z - (r i : ℂ))⁻¹

/-- `rootProduct` is the Tier-21 characteristic determinant of the
real-diagonal matrix: the polynomial side and the operator side agree. -/
theorem rootProduct_eq_charDet {N : ℕ} (r : Fin N → ℝ) :
    rootProduct r = fun z => charDet (realDiagonal r) z := by
  funext z
  unfold rootProduct
  rw [charDet_realDiagonal_eq_prod]

/-- **Each real pole is anti-Herglotz.** For a real `r` and `Im z > 0`,
`Im (1/(z − r)) = −Im z / |z − r|² ≤ 0`. -/
theorem rootSumResponse_antiHerglotz {N : ℕ} (r : Fin N → ℝ) :
    AntiHerglotzResponseLaw (rootSumResponse r) := by
  intro z hz
  unfold rootSumResponse
  rw [Complex.im_sum]
  apply Finset.sum_nonpos
  intro i _
  rw [Complex.inv_im, Complex.sub_im, Complex.ofReal_im, sub_zero]
  have hnum : -z.im ≤ 0 := by linarith
  exact div_nonpos_of_nonpos_of_nonneg hnum (Complex.normSq_nonneg _)

/-- **Logarithmic-derivative identity.** Off the roots, the log-derivative
of the real-rooted polynomial `rootProduct r` equals the pole sum
`rootSumResponse r`. This is the partial-fraction identity
`P'/P = ∑ 1/(z − rᵢ)` for `P(z) = ∏ (z − rᵢ)`. -/
theorem rootProduct_logDeriv_eq_rootSum {N : ℕ} (r : Fin N → ℝ) (z : ℂ)
    (hz : ∀ i : Fin N, z ≠ (r i : ℂ)) :
    deriv (rootProduct r) z / rootProduct r z = rootSumResponse r z := by
  have hfac : ∀ i : Fin N, z - (r i : ℂ) ≠ 0 :=
    fun i => sub_ne_zero.mpr (hz i)
  have hP : rootProduct r z ≠ 0 := by
    unfold rootProduct
    exact Finset.prod_ne_zero_iff.mpr (fun i _ => hfac i)
  have hkey : ∀ i ∈ (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin N)),
      HasDerivAt (fun w : ℂ => w - (r i : ℂ)) (1 : ℂ) z :=
    fun i _ => by simpa using (hasDerivAt_id z).sub_const (r i : ℂ)
  have hderiv : HasDerivAt (rootProduct r)
      (∑ i : Fin N,
        (∏ j ∈ (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin N)).erase i, (z - (r j : ℂ)))
          • (1 : ℂ)) z :=
    HasDerivAt.finset_prod hkey
  have hd : deriv (rootProduct r) z
      = ∑ i : Fin N,
          ∏ j ∈ (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin N)).erase i, (z - (r j : ℂ)) := by
    rw [hderiv.deriv]
    simp only [smul_eq_mul, mul_one]
  rw [hd, div_eq_iff hP]
  unfold rootSumResponse rootProduct
  rw [Finset.sum_mul]
  refine Finset.sum_congr rfl (fun i _ => ?_)
  rw [← Finset.mul_prod_erase (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin N))
        (fun j => z - (r j : ℂ)) (Finset.mem_univ i),
      ← mul_assoc, inv_mul_cancel₀ (hfac i), one_mul]

/-- **Flagship (finite, unconditional).** The logarithmic derivative of
*any* real-rooted polynomial is an anti-Herglotz response.

On the upper half-plane there is no side condition: a point `z` with
`Im z > 0` can never equal a real root, so the partial-fraction
identity holds everywhere it is needed. This is the "beautiful theorem"
that turns real-rootedness into spectral positivity. -/
theorem realRooted_logDerivative_antiHerglotz {N : ℕ} (r : Fin N → ℝ) :
    AntiHerglotzResponseLaw
      (fun z => deriv (rootProduct r) z / rootProduct r z) := by
  intro z hz
  have hznr : ∀ i : Fin N, z ≠ (r i : ℂ) := by
    intro i hcontra
    have hzim : z.im = 0 := by rw [hcontra]; exact Complex.ofReal_im (r i)
    rw [hzim] at hz
    exact absurd hz (lt_irrefl 0)
  show (deriv (rootProduct r) z / rootProduct r z).im ≤ 0
  rw [rootProduct_logDeriv_eq_rootSum r z hznr]
  exact rootSumResponse_antiHerglotz r z hz

-- --- Tier 73.3 — Herglotz positivity survives limits ----------------

/-- **Anti-Herglotz survives pointwise limits.** Anti-Herglotz is a
pointwise closed condition (`Im R(z) ≤ 0`), so it transfers from a
sequence of responses to their pointwise limit — in particular to a
locally uniform limit. This is the step that carries the positivity of
the finite real-rooted sections to the limiting zeta response. -/
theorem antiHerglotz_of_tendsto {R : ℕ → ℂ → ℂ} {Rlim : ℂ → ℂ}
    (hconv : ∀ z : ℂ,
      Filter.Tendsto (fun N => R N z) Filter.atTop (nhds (Rlim z)))
    (hanti : ∀ N, AntiHerglotzResponseLaw (R N)) :
    AntiHerglotzResponseLaw Rlim := by
  intro z hz
  have htends : Filter.Tendsto (fun N : ℕ => (R N z).im) Filter.atTop
      (nhds (Rlim z).im) :=
    (Complex.continuous_im.tendsto _).comp (hconv z)
  exact le_of_tendsto' htends (fun N => hanti N z hz)

/-- **Herglotz survives pointwise limits** — the twin of
`antiHerglotz_of_tendsto` for the other sign convention. -/
theorem herglotz_of_tendsto {R : ℕ → ℂ → ℂ} {Rlim : ℂ → ℂ}
    (hconv : ∀ z : ℂ,
      Filter.Tendsto (fun N => R N z) Filter.atTop (nhds (Rlim z)))
    (hherg : ∀ N, HerglotzResponseLaw (R N)) :
    HerglotzResponseLaw Rlim := by
  intro z hz
  have htends : Filter.Tendsto (fun N : ℕ => (R N z).im) Filter.atTop
      (nhds (Rlim z).im) :=
    (Complex.continuous_im.tendsto _).comp (hconv z)
  exact ge_of_tendsto' htends (fun N => hherg N z hz)

-- --- Tier 73.4 — Concrete Hermite–Biehler dominance -----------------

/-- **Sharp conjugate** `E#(z) = conj(E(conj z))` — the de Branges
reflection of `E`. -/
def SharpConjugate (E : ℂ → ℂ) : ℂ → ℂ :=
  fun z => (starRingEnd ℂ) (E ((starRingEnd ℂ) z))

/-- The sharp conjugate is an involution: `E## = E`. -/
theorem sharpConjugate_involutive (E : ℂ → ℂ) :
    SharpConjugate (SharpConjugate E) = E := by
  funext z
  simp only [SharpConjugate, Complex.conj_conj]

/-- **Hermite–Biehler dominance** as a *concrete inequality*: `E`
strictly dominates its sharp conjugate on the open upper half-plane,
`‖E#(z)‖ < ‖E(z)‖` for `Im z > 0`. This replaces the abstract `Prop`
field of the Tier-36 `HermiteBiehlerFunction`. -/
def HermiteBiehlerDominance (E : ℂ → ℂ) : Prop :=
  ∀ z : ℂ, UpperHalfPlane z → ‖SharpConjugate E z‖ < ‖E z‖

/-- **Concrete Hermite–Biehler function.** The Tier-36
`HermiteBiehlerFunction` with its positivity gate spelled out as the
real dominance inequality and a genuine non-vanishing condition. -/
structure HermiteBiehlerConcrete (E : ℂ → ℂ) where
  /-- `E` is entire. -/
  entire : AnalyticOnNhd ℂ E Set.univ
  /-- The concrete upper-half-plane dominance inequality. -/
  dominance : HermiteBiehlerDominance E
  /-- `E` has no zeros on the real axis. -/
  noRealZeros : ∀ x : ℝ, E (x : ℂ) ≠ 0

/-- A concrete Hermite–Biehler function forgets to the abstract Tier-36
`HermiteBiehlerFunction`: the upgrade path from `Prop`-scaffold to real
inequality is one-directional and explicit. -/
def HermiteBiehlerConcrete.toAbstract {E : ℂ → ℂ}
    (_H : HermiteBiehlerConcrete E) : HermiteBiehlerFunction E where
  upperHalfPlaneDominance := HermiteBiehlerDominance E
  noRealDegeneracy := ∀ x : ℝ, E (x : ℂ) ≠ 0

-- --- Tier 73.5 — Monotone boundary phase ----------------------------

/-- **Monotone phase law.** A Hermite–Biehler function has a
real-axis phase `φ(t) = arg E(t)` whose derivative is strictly
positive — `φ` is the scattering phase and its derivative is the
spectral density. The single inequality field is concrete. -/
structure MonotonePhaseLaw where
  /-- The boundary phase function. -/
  phase : ℝ → ℝ
  /-- The phase derivative is strictly positive. -/
  phaseDerivativePositive : ∀ t : ℝ, 0 < deriv phase t

/-- A monotone phase law's phase is strictly increasing — the phase
counts spectral points monotonically. -/
theorem MonotonePhaseLaw.phase_strictMono (M : MonotonePhaseLaw) :
    StrictMono M.phase :=
  strictMono_of_deriv_pos M.phaseDerivativePositive

-- --- Tier 73.6 — The Prime–Herglotz Law -----------------------------

/-- **The Prime–Herglotz Law.** A classification object for the zeta
target `Ξ`:

* a Tier-21 real-rooted polynomial approximation to `Ξ` (the finite
  Hermitian sections), and
* a limiting `response` to which the section log-derivatives converge
  pointwise.

Given this data the response is *forced* to be anti-Herglotz
(`response_antiHerglotz`) and `Ξ` is *forced* to have only real zeros
(`implies_RH`). The law packages the visible side (the response) of
the Hilbert–Pólya picture. -/
structure PrimeHerglotzLaw (Xi : ℂ → ℂ) where
  /-- The real-rooted polynomial approximation (Tier 21). -/
  approx : RealRootedPolynomialApproximation Xi
  /-- The limiting logarithmic-derivative response. -/
  response : ℂ → ℂ
  /-- The section log-derivatives converge pointwise to `response`. -/
  responseConverges : ∀ z : ℂ,
    Filter.Tendsto
      (fun N : ℕ => deriv (rootProduct (approx.roots N)) z
                      / rootProduct (approx.roots N) z)
      Filter.atTop (nhds (response z))

/-- **The response of a Prime–Herglotz law is anti-Herglotz.** Each
finite section log-derivative is anti-Herglotz
(`realRooted_logDerivative_antiHerglotz`); the property survives the
pointwise limit (`antiHerglotz_of_tendsto`). The positivity is *proved*,
not assumed. -/
theorem PrimeHerglotzLaw.response_antiHerglotz {Xi : ℂ → ℂ}
    (H : PrimeHerglotzLaw Xi) :
    AntiHerglotzResponseLaw H.response :=
  antiHerglotz_of_tendsto H.responseConverges
    (fun N => realRooted_logDerivative_antiHerglotz (H.approx.roots N))

/-- **A Prime–Herglotz law implies the real-zero conclusion.** Routes
the real-rooted approximation through the Tier-16 Diamond. -/
theorem PrimeHerglotzLaw.implies_RH {Xi : ℂ → ℂ}
    (H : PrimeHerglotzLaw Xi) (hHurwitz : HurwitzZeroTransferPrinciple) :
    HasOnlyRealZeros Xi :=
  realRooted_diamond_limit H.approx hHurwitz

/-- **Flagship — the Prime–Herglotz de Branges Diamond.** A
Prime–Herglotz law simultaneously delivers:
1. `Ξ` has only real zeros (RH-type conclusion), and
2. its logarithmic-derivative response is anti-Herglotz.

The arithmetic/response side and the spectral/zero side are one
theorem, conditional only on the abstract Hurwitz principle. -/
theorem primeHerglotz_deBranges_diamond {Xi : ℂ → ℂ}
    (H : PrimeHerglotzLaw Xi) (hHurwitz : HurwitzZeroTransferPrinciple) :
    HasOnlyRealZeros Xi ∧ AntiHerglotzResponseLaw H.response :=
  ⟨H.implies_RH hHurwitz, H.response_antiHerglotz⟩

/-- **Critical-line form** of the Prime–Herglotz Diamond. -/
theorem primeHerglotz_critical_line {xi : ℂ → ℂ}
    (H : PrimeHerglotzLaw (criticalPullback xi))
    (hHurwitz : HurwitzZeroTransferPrinciple) :
    HasOnlyCriticalLineZeros xi :=
  (criticalLineZeros_iff_realZeros_pullback xi).mpr (H.implies_RH hHurwitz)

/-- **No-go (the falsification lever).** A response that fails the
anti-Herglotz law can never be the limiting log-derivative response of
*any* Hilbert–Pólya real-rooted approximation: no `PrimeHerglotzLaw`
can carry it. The sieve run in reverse. -/
theorem no_primeHerglotz_of_response_not_antiHerglotz {Xi : ℂ → ℂ}
    {R : ℂ → ℂ} (hbad : ¬ AntiHerglotzResponseLaw R)
    (H : PrimeHerglotzLaw Xi) :
    H.response ≠ R := by
  intro hEq
  exact hbad (hEq ▸ H.response_antiHerglotz)

/-! ## Tier 73 Status Summary

Tier 73 lands the **Prime–Herglotz de Branges Gate** — the shift from
hunting the operator to forcing the *response*.

Unconditional positivity engine:
* `rootSumResponse_antiHerglotz` — `∑ 1/(z − rᵢ)` over real roots has
  non-positive imaginary part on the upper half-plane.
* `rootProduct_logDeriv_eq_rootSum` — the partial-fraction identity
  `P'/P = ∑ 1/(z − rᵢ)` for `P = ∏(z − rᵢ)`.
* **`realRooted_logDerivative_antiHerglotz`** — the log-derivative of
  any real-rooted polynomial is anti-Herglotz, with *no* side
  condition on the upper half-plane.
* `antiHerglotz_of_tendsto` / `herglotz_of_tendsto` — the response
  laws survive pointwise (hence locally uniform) limits.
* `rootProduct_eq_charDet` — ties the polynomial side to the Tier-21
  characteristic determinant `charDet (realDiagonal r)`.

Concrete de Branges objects (replacing Tier-36 `Prop`-scaffold):
* `UpperHalfPlane`, `SharpConjugate` (+ `sharpConjugate_involutive`),
  `HermiteBiehlerDominance` — the real dominance inequality.
* `HermiteBiehlerConcrete` (+ `.toAbstract`) — the upgrade path.
* `MonotonePhaseLaw` (+ `.phase_strictMono`) — the boundary phase with
  its one concrete inequality field.

Classification flagship:
* `HerglotzResponseLaw` / `AntiHerglotzResponseLaw` (+
  `antiHerglotz_iff_neg_herglotz`) — the visible positivity gate.
* `PrimeHerglotzLaw` — real-rooted approximation + convergent response.
* `PrimeHerglotzLaw.response_antiHerglotz` — the response positivity is
  *proved*, not a field.
* `PrimeHerglotzLaw.implies_RH`, `primeHerglotz_deBranges_diamond`,
  `primeHerglotz_critical_line` — RH-type conclusions via the Diamond.
* **`no_primeHerglotz_of_response_not_antiHerglotz`** — the sieve in
  reverse: failure of anti-Herglotz positivity kills the candidate.

The deep open content stays cleanly isolated: producing a
`PrimeHerglotzLaw Ξ` for the genuine completed zeta — i.e. a real-rooted
approximation whose log-derivatives converge — would discharge RH
modulo Hurwitz. No GoldenAlgebra-specific axiom appears in any Tier 73
proof. -/

