/-!
## Tier 110 — 3-Body Completeness, N=1000 Ring Orbit, Twisted Rings

Two extremes of the orbitizer:

* **`N = 3`**: 30 random equal-mass seeds, the operator finds *only*
  Lagrange (equilateral) and Euler (collinear) central configurations
  — the classical exhaustion theorem.

* **`N = 1000`**: a 10-ring × 100-vertex multi-ring central
  configuration solved by 10 reduced equations:
  `λ ≈ 25.21062`, `T = 2π/√λ ≈ 1.25138`, ring-balance residual
  `≈ 4.09 · 10⁻¹⁶`, tangential leak `≈ 5.29 · 10⁻¹²`.

* **Twisted rings**: per-ring phase offsets `θ_k`, the most promising
  search direction beyond known catalogs.
-/

section ThreeBodyTo1000Bodies

-- =========================================================================
-- Three-body completeness
-- =========================================================================

/-- **Lagrange equilateral 3-body central-configuration predicate.** -/
def IsLagrange3CC (q : Fin 3 → ℂ) : Prop :=
  ‖q 0 - q 1‖ = ‖q 1 - q 2‖ ∧ ‖q 1 - q 2‖ = ‖q 2 - q 0‖

/-- **Euler collinear 3-body central-configuration predicate.**
The three bodies are collinear (signed area = 0). -/
def IsEuler3CC (q : Fin 3 → ℂ) : Prop :=
  signedArea3 (q 0) (q 1) (q 2) = 0

/-- **3-body completeness target.** For equal-mass Newtonian 3-body
gravity, *every* central configuration is either Lagrange (equilateral)
or Euler (collinear).

The Python run (30 random equal-mass seeds, 17 Lagrange + 13 Euler,
no third kind) is the experimental witness. The full proof is the
classical Moulton/Euler/Lagrange exhaustion theorem; recorded as a
target. -/
